The Assocication of Sotheast Asian Nations ‚Äì ASEAN for short, is an association that today consists of 10 Sothest Asian states. In 1967, Thailand, Indonesia, Philiphines,Singapore and Malaysia founded ASEAN. The aim was to improve economic, political and social cooperation. Another objective was to balance polotical conflicts between these countries that existed as a consequence of decolonization and post- colonial state-building. During Cold War, ASEAN members wanted to contain the influence of commuism in their region. Time changed, old enemies became new partnes and in the second half of 1990s Vietnam, Laos, Myanmar and Combodia joined ASEAN. The collapse of the USSR, the founding of WTO and a financial crisis in Asia prompted members to deepen their relations and adapt to the new situation. In 2000s, free trade agreements were conclud ed with India, China, South Korea, Austrialia, New Zealand and Japan. In the future, the entire region will be merged into one large free trade zone. Since 2001, the ‚ÄúASEAN Summit‚Äù take places annually. It is a meeting of the heads of states and government, where current problems are discussed and solution are worked out. On 15th December 2008, the ASEAN Charter came into force, giving the association the status of legal person Principles of non- intervention and concensual decision taking remained unchanged by the charter
